---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import TreeWorld from '../components/TreeWorld.astro';
---

<Base
  active="how"
  title="How storytree works"
  description="The living story-tree map, the review gates where nothing ships without proof, building in parallel by people and AI agents, and an open record you can check directly."
>
  <!-- intro -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">How it works</p>
      <h1>A project that grows like a garden.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        The <a href="/constitution/">constitution</a> says what storytree believes. This page is
        the how: the pieces that turn "build software in the open" from a nice idea into something
        you can actually watch happen — and check.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- the living map + tree demo -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="prose">
        <p class="eyebrow">1 · The living map</p>
        <h2>Every project is a tree of stories.</h2>
        <p>
          Instead of a roadmap hidden in someone's head, a storytree project is a living map you
          can see. Each <strong>story</strong> is a self-contained piece of the software — "the
          part that sends invitations", "the part that draws the map". As work happens, the map
          grows: new stories sprout, dependencies form roads between them, and each one changes
          colour as it earns its place.
        </p>
      </div>

      <TreeWorld />

      <div class="prose legend-note">
        <p class="muted">
          A made-up example project, shown in storytree's real map view. Hover or tap a tree to
          read what it is. (This is fictional data — a toy "garden planner" app — not storytree's
          own roadmap.)
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- the grain -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">2 · The grain</p>
      <h2>Big things are made of small, provable things.</h2>
      <p>
        Zoom into a story and it's made of smaller pieces, each one small enough to prove on its
        own. The idea is old and boring and it works: you don't get to call something "done"
        because you feel good about it — you get to call it done when there's evidence.
      </p>
      <div class="grid grid--3 ladder">
        <div class="card">
          <span class="dot dot--healthy"></span><strong>Story</strong>
          <p class="muted">A whole, useful capability — the kind of thing a newcomer can point at. Proven by walking through it end to end, the way a real person would use it.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="dot dot--healthy"></span><strong>Capability</strong>
          <p class="muted">An organ inside a story. Proven by testing its parts wired together, for real — no faking the hard bits.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="dot dot--healthy"></span><strong>Contract</strong>
          <p class="muted">A single behaviour, pinned down by one focused automated test. The smallest brick.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- the gates -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap band2">
      <div class="band2__inner prose">
        <p class="eyebrow">3 · The gates</p>
        <h2>Nothing ships without proof.</h2>
        <p>
          This is the load-bearing rule. Between "someone proposed this" and "this is part of the
          software" sits a <strong>gate</strong> — and the gate refuses anything that can't show
          its working. A piece only turns green when a test that was <em>failing</em> is made to
          pass for the right reason. No hand-waving a thing into "done"; no quietly marking your
          own homework.
        </p>
        <ul class="checks">
          <li>An idea or a concern can come from anyone — you don't have to write code to raise one.</li>
          <li>It gets discussed in the open, where the reasoning is on the record.</li>
          <li>If it becomes work, that work has to pass its gate before it counts — proof first.</li>
          <li>A human still says the final yes before anything lands. A green light is a request for review, not an automatic merge.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- parallel -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">4 · The builders</p>
      <h2>People and AI agents, building in parallel.</h2>
      <p>
        Lots of the building is done by <strong>AI&nbsp;agents</strong> — many of them, working at
        once, each growing a different part of the tree. storytree is the layer on top: the place
        you watch them work, steer them, review what they produce, and decide what's allowed in.
        Think of it less as "an AI agent that writes code" and more as a control room for a whole
        workforce of them — with humans firmly in charge of what's true and what ships.
      </p>
      <p>
        Because it's all on one shared map, the work can be massively parallel without becoming
        chaos: you can see who's touching what, where the proof stands, and what's still just an
        idea.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- transparency -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">5 · The honesty mechanism</p>
      <h2>An open record you can check.</h2>
      <p>
        Every decision and the reasoning behind it is kept on the record, not summarised away
        after the fact. That's the foundation of the whole trust model: you don't have to take
        anyone's word, because you can check.
      </p>
      <p>
        There's an honest gap here, and we'd rather name it than paper over it: today the people
        running storytree could still quietly edit that record. Making it tamper-evident — and,
        further out, letting you simply <strong>ask the project</strong> in plain language against
        its whole record — is exactly the kind of thing the <a href="/roadmap/">roadmap</a> lays
        out: what's built, what's next, and what's honestly still ahead of us.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- cta -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap prose cta-card">
      <h2>That's the experiment.</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        Can building this way stay fair and trustworthy <em>because</em> it's open? We don't fully
        know yet — that's the point. If it resonates, the door to ask is open.
      </p>
      <div class="hero__cta">
        <a class="btn btn--primary" href="/contact/">Ask to come in →</a>
        <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="/constitution/">Read what we commit to</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .legend-note { margin-top: 1rem; }
  .legend-note p { font-size: 0.92rem; margin: 0; }
  .ladder { margin-top: 1.3rem; }
  .ladder .card p { margin: 0.4rem 0 0; }
  .ladder .card strong { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 1.12rem; }

  .band2 {
    background: var(--surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-left: 5px solid var(--evergreen);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    box-shadow: var(--shadow);
  }
  .band2__inner { padding: clamp(1.6rem, 4vw, 2.8rem); max-width: 46rem; }
  .checks { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 1.2rem 0 0; display: grid; gap: 0.7rem; }
  .checks li { position: relative; padding-left: 1.9rem; color: var(--ink-soft); }
  .checks li::before {
    content: ""; position: absolute; left: 0; top: 0.35em;
    width: 1.15rem; height: 1.15rem; border-radius: 999px;
    background: var(--evergreen-soft);
    box-shadow: inset 0 0 0 2px var(--evergreen);
  }
  .checks li::after {
    content: ""; position: absolute; left: 0.34rem; top: 0.62em;
    width: 0.42rem; height: 0.24rem; border-left: 2px solid var(--evergreen); border-bottom: 2px solid var(--evergreen);
    transform: rotate(-45deg);
  }
  .cta-card { text-align: center; max-width: 38rem; }
  .cta-card .hero__cta { justify-content: center; }
  .em, .how em { font-style: italic; }
  em { font-style: italic; }
</style>
